            <block class="mm_textBlock mm_padder">
                <p>We know that food can be sweet, salty, 
                    <sSpan class="mm_inlineNumber">1</sSpan><droppable id="droppable_1" example="y" rank="5">bitter</droppable>,
                    or sour. But do you know what umami is? Umami means "tasty/yummy" in 
                    <sSpan class="mm_inlineNumber">2</sSpan><droppable id="droppable_2" rank="2">Japanese</droppable>
                    . It’s a flavor that’s found in meat, mushrooms, seaweed, and "smelly" foods like cheese. It makes everything taste better and everyone likes it, even babies! A lot of Asian food tastes of umami and that is why it’s so 
                    <sSpan class="mm_inlineNumber">3</sSpan><droppable id="droppable_3" rank="3">delicious</droppable>
                    .</p>
                <p>Food is often tastier when you add salt. But it isn’t good to eat too much 
                    <sSpan class="mm_inlineNumber">4</sSpan><droppable id="droppable_4" rank="6">salty</droppable>
                    food so 
                    <sSpan class="mm_inlineNumber">5</sSpan><droppable id="droppable_5" rank="4">chefs</droppable>
                    are now using umami. It can make food 
                    <sSpan class="mm_inlineNumber">6</sSpan><droppable id="droppable_6" rank="1">taste</droppable>
                    really good.</p>
            </block>
        </block>
    </main>
